  "prompt": "What if a cricket ball hits a batsman\u2019s helmet and then goes to the boundary?",
  "response": "In cricket, if a ball hits a batsman's helmet and then goes to the boundary, the runs are awarded as four byes if the ball does not touch the bat or if the batsman is making a legitimate attempt to evade the ball. This is because the ball has not made contact with the bat and has traveled to the boundary after hitting the helmet.\n\nIf, however, the ball deflects off the helmet and subsequently hits the bat or glove before reaching the boundary, it would be counted as runs scored off the bat, and any runs scored would be recorded as runs accrued by the batsman, not byes.\n\nRegardless of how the runs are scored, the batsman may also receive medical attention if needed, especially if a helmet impact is significant. ",
